In its bid to make Onitsha River Port functional and to decongest Lagos Ports, the National Inland Waterways Authority (NIWA) has outlined plans to move containers from Lagos Ports to Onitsha River Port through Burutu Port in Delta. NIWA’s General Manager, Corporate Affairs, Mr Jibril Darda`u disclosed this in a statement made available to the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN), on Monday, in Onitsha. Darda`u explained that in order to put the plans into operation, NIWA is to engage the services of a private firm, Akewa Colmar Terminal Limited (ACTL). HOW NIGERIAN MEN CAN NOW NATURALLY STOP PREMATURE EJACULATION, LOW SPERM COUNT AND OTHER MEN'S SEXUAL NEEDS. MADAM ALWAYS WANTS IT BIGGER, STRONGER AND LONG-LASTING!!! “The idea of hauling containers via Burutu Ports to Onitsha River port is to deliberately avoid the two small bridges of Gbarekolo and Bomandi. “The two bridges are tiny and shallow for sea moving badges or vessels to ply through. FG Using FTZs To Reduce High Unemployment Rate, Insecurity BREAKING: [Video] Ogun Receives 100,000 Dozes Of COVID-19 Vaccines “That is why ACTL is considering the route from Lagos Ports to Burutu Port then to Onitsha River Port as final destination,” he explained. The general manager said the agency was targeting hauling 1,000 containers  per trip, from Lagos Ports to Onitsha River Port, in four days, adding that NIWA was engaging the Nigeria Ports Authority (NPA) and other stakeholders, to facilitate the commencement of the cargo haulage. Darda`u expressed the readiness of NIWA to partner with ACTL, in achieving the historic transshipment from Lagos Ports via Burutu Port to Onitsha River Port as final destination. (NAN)